  "prompt": "What is the difference between Shall and Will?",
  "response": "\"Shall\" and \"will\" are both modal verbs in English used to express future actions, intentions, or obligations. While they are often used interchangeably in everyday conversation, there are subtle differences in their usage, especially in formal contexts and between different varieties of English (such as British and American English). Here's a breakdown of their differences:\n\n### 1. Traditional Usage\n\n**First Person (I, We):**\n- **Shall**: Traditionally used to express simple future.\n  - *Example*: \"I shall return by evening.\"\n- **Will**: Used to express determination or promise.\n  - *Example*: \"We will finish the project on time.\"\n\n**Second and Third Person (You, He, She, They):**\n- **Shall**: Rarely used; traditionally used to express commands or obligations.\n  - *Example*: \"You shall not pass.\"\n- **Will**: Used to express simple future.\n  - *Example*: \"They will arrive tomorrow.\"\n\n### 2. Modern Usage\n\nIn contemporary English, especially in everyday speech, \"will\" has largely supplanted \"shall\" except in specific contexts. Here's how they are commonly used today:\n\n- **\"Will\"** is predominantly used for:\n  - **Future Predictions**: \"It will rain tomorrow.\"\n  - **Promises/Volition**: \"I will help you with your homework.\"\n  - **Decisions Made at the Moment of Speaking**: \"I think I'll have tea.\"\n\n- **\"Shall\"** is often reserved for:\n  - **Formal or Legal Documents**: \"The tenant shall pay rent on the first of each month.\"\n  - **Offers and Suggestions (primarily in British English)**:\n    - *Example*: \"Shall we dance?\" or \"Shall I open the window?\"\n  - **Expressions of Necessity or Obligation** (more common in British English): \"You shall follow the rules.\"\n\n### 3. Differences Between British and American English\n\n- **British English**:\n  - More likely to use \"shall\" in formal writing and legal contexts.\n  - Uses \"shall\" in questions and offers/suggestions more frequently than American English.\n    - *Example*: \"Shall we go?\" is more common in British English.\n\n- **American English**:\n  - Prefers \"will\" over \"shall\" in most contexts.\n  - \"Shall\" is often perceived as formal, old-fashioned, or legalistic.\n    - *Example*: Americans are more likely to say, \"Should we go?\" instead of \"Shall we go?\"\n\n### 4. Legal and Formal Contexts\n\nIn legal documents, \"shall\" has a specific implication of obligation or duty, making it enforceable:\n\n- *Example*: \"The lessee shall maintain the property in good condition.\"\n\nHere, \"shall\" imposes a requirement, whereas \"will\" might merely state a future action without the same level of obligation.\n\n### 5. Summary\n\n- **Use \"will\"** for most future expressions, promises, and in both American and British English for everyday contexts.\n- **Use \"shall\"** in formal, legal, or very formal contexts, and primarily in British English for offers, suggestions, and to express obligation.\n- In modern, informal English, especially in American English, \"shall\" is rarely used outside of legal or highly formal language.\n\n### Examples for Clarity\n\n1. **Promise/Determination**:\n   - *I will study hard for the exam.*\n   \n2. **Formal Obligation**:\n   - *The contractor shall complete the work by December.*\n\n3. **Offer/Suggestion (British English)**:\n   - *Shall we meet for lunch tomorrow?*\n\n4. **Legal Requirement**:\n   - *Companies shall comply with all safety regulations.*\n\nUnderstanding the nuances between \"shall\" and \"will\" can enhance precision in communication, especially in formal writing and legal documents. However, in everyday conversation, using \"will\" is generally sufficient and widely accepted.",
